  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "A chart of accounts is the complete, structured list of all accounts an entity uses to record financial transactions. It assigns each account a name, a number, and a type (asset, liability, equity, revenue, or expense). The chart defines what the entity can track and report — an expense that doesn\u0026rsquo;t have its own account gets lumped into a broader category, invisible to anyone reviewing the financial statements.\nAccount numbering typically follows a convention that groups accounts by type:\n",
